# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bile-acid
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bile-acid/17-ketosteroid] A **ketosteroid**, or an **oxosteroid**, is a steroid in which a hydrogen atom has been replaced with a ketone (C=O) group.
[src:bile-acid/17-ketosteroid] A **17-ketosteroid** is a ketosteroid in which the ketone is located specifically at the C17 position (in the upper right corner of most structure diagrams).
[src:bile-acid/17-ketosteroid] 17-Ketosteroids are endogenous steroid hormones.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxypregnenolone] 17α-Hydroxypregnenolone is considered a prohormone in the formation of dehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA), itself a prohormone of the sex steroids.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxypregnenolone] This conversion is mediated by the enzyme 17,20 lyase.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxypregnenolone] As such 17α-hydroxypregnenolone represents an intermediary in the Δ5 pathway that leads from pregnenolone to DHEA.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxypregnenolone] 17α-Hydroxypregnenolone is also converted to 17α-hydroxyprogesterone, a prohormone for glucocorticosteroids and androstenedione through the activity of 3α-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxypregnenolone] Measurements of 17α-hydroxypregnenolone are useful in the diagnosis of certain forms of congenital adrenal hyperplasia.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxypregnenolone] In patients with congenital adrenal hyperplasia due to 3β-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase deficiency 17α-hydroxypregnenolone is increased, while in patients with congenital adrenal hyperplasia due to 17α-hydroxylase deficiency levels are low to absent.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxypregnenolone] 17α-hydroxypregnenolone is a known neuromodulator as its acts in the central nervous system.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxypregnenolone] Specifically, it is known to modulate locomotion.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxyprogesterone] 17α-OHP is an agonist of the progesterone receptor (PR) similarly to progesterone, albeit weakly in comparison.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxyprogesterone] In addition, it is an antagonist of the mineralocorticoid receptor (MR) as well as a partial agonist of the glucocorticoid receptor (GR), albeit with very low potency (EC50 >100-fold less relative to cortisol) at the latter site, also similarly to progesterone.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxyprogesterone] 17α-OHP is derived from progesterone via 17α-hydroxylase (encoded by CYP17A1).
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxyprogesterone] 17α-OHP increases in the third trimester of pregnancy primarily due to fetal adrenal production.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxyprogesterone] This steroid is primarily produced in the adrenal glands and to some degree in the gonads, specifically the corpus luteum of the ovary.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxyprogesterone] Normal levels are 3-90 ng/dl in children, and in women, 20-100 ng/dl prior to ovulation, and 100-500 ng/dl during the luteal phase.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxyprogesterone] Measurements of levels of 17α-OHP are useful in the evaluation of patients with suspected congenital adrenal hyperplasia as the typical enzymes that are defective, namely 21-hydroxylase and 11β-hydroxylase, lead to a build-up of 17α-OHP.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxyprogesterone] In contrast, the rare patient with 17α-hydroxylase deficiency will have very low or undetectable levels of 17α-OHP.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxyprogesterone] 17α-OHP levels can also be used to measure contribution of progestational activity of the corpus luteum during pregnancy as progesterone but note, 17α-OHP is also contributed by the placenta.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxyprogesterone] Immunoassays like RIA (radioimmunoassay) or IRMA (immunoradiometric assay) used to clinically determine 17α-OHP are prone to cross-reactivity with the 17α-OHP steroid precursors and their sulphated conjugates.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxyprogesterone] Gas or liquid chromatography and mass spectrometry (e.g.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxyprogesterone] LC-MS/MS) achieves greater specificity than immunoassays.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxyprogesterone] Although 17α-OHP has not been used as a medication, its pharmacokinetics have been studied and reviewed.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxyprogesterone] Esters of 17α-OHP, such as hydroxyprogesterone caproate and, to a far lesser extent, hydroxyprogesterone acetate and hydroxyprogesterone heptanoate, have been used in medicine as progestins.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxyprogesterone] 17α-OHP is the parent compound of a class of progestins referred to as the *17α-hydroxyprogesterone derivatives*.
[src:bile-acid/17α-hydroxyprogesterone] Among others, this class of drugs includes chlormadinone acetate, cyproterone acetate, hydroxyprogesterone caproate, medroxyprogesterone acetate, and megestrol acetate.
[src:bile-acid/22r-hydroxycholesterol] It is an agonist of the liver X receptor.
[src:bile-acid/24s-hydroxycholesterol] 24S-HC is produced by a hydroxy group substitution at carbon number 24 in cholesterol, catalyzed by the enzyme cholesterol 24-hydroxylase (CYP46A1).
[src:bile-acid/24s-hydroxycholesterol] 24S-HC binds to apolipoproteins such as apoE, apoJ, and apoA1 to form HDL-like complexes which can cross the blood–brain barrier more easily than free cholesterol.
[src:bile-acid/24s-hydroxycholesterol] Thus, 24S-HC production serves as one of several counterbalancing mechanisms for cholesterol synthesis in the brain.
[src:bile-acid/24s-hydroxycholesterol] After entering general blood circulation and traveling to the liver, 24S-HC can be sulfated, glucuronidated, or converted into bile acids, which can ultimately be excreted.
[src:bile-acid/24s-hydroxycholesterol] 24S-HC is an agonist of liver X receptors, a class of nuclear receptors that sense oxysterols.
[src:bile-acid/24s-hydroxycholesterol] In the brain, liver X receptor beta is the primary LXR type, which interacts with 24S-HC.
[src:bile-acid/24s-hydroxycholesterol] 24S-HC levels sensed by LXRs can regulate the expression of SREBP mRNA and protein, which in turn regulate cholesterol synthesis and fatty acid synthesis.
[src:bile-acid/24s-hydroxycholesterol] 24S-HC may participate in several aspects of brain development and function, such as axon and dendrite growth or synaptogenesis, as well as acting as a positive allosteric modulator of NMDA receptors.
[src:bile-acid/24s-hydroxycholesterol] Regulation of 24S-HC metabolism in neurons may play a role in their health and function, as well as their response to injury or disease.
[src:bile-acid/24s-hydroxycholesterol] Blood plasma levels of 24S-HC may be altered after acute brain injuries such as stroke or in neurodegenerative diseases such as Alzheimer's disease, Huntington's disease, and multiple sclerosis.
[src:bile-acid/27-hydroxycholesterol] A link between high cholesterol and breast cancer has been identified, and it has been proposed that this is due to 27-HC production by CYP27A1.
[src:bile-acid/27-hydroxycholesterol] Because of its estrogenic action, 27-HC stimulates the growth of ER-positive breast cancer cells, and has been implicated in limiting the effectiveness of aromatase inhibitors in the treatment of breast cancer.
[src:bile-acid/27-hydroxycholesterol] As such, identified CYP27A1 inhibitors, including the marketed drugs anastrozole, fadrozole, bicalutamide, dexmedetomidine, ravuconazole, and posaconazole, have been proposed as potential adjuvant therapies in ER-positive breast cancer.
[src:bile-acid/5α-androst-16-en-3α-ol] Androstenol, or a derivative, is found in black truffles.
[src:bile-acid/5α-androst-16-en-3α-ol] This was offered as an explanation for how pigs locate them deep in the ground: Androstenol is produced in the saliva of male pigs.
[src:bile-acid/5α-androst-16-en-3α-ol] However, experiments in France using pigs to scent truffles, truffle scent extract, and purified androstenol showed that pigs responded to the first two (actually trying to eat dirt containing the truffle extract), but ignored the androstenol.
[src:bile-acid/5α-androst-16-en-3α-ol] A stereoisomer of androstenol, 3β-androstenol (5α-androst-16-en-3β-ol), is also endogenous to humans (as well as to pigs), behaving as a pheromone and contributing to axillary odor.
[src:bile-acid/5α-androst-16-en-3α-ol] In humans and boars, androstenol is biosynthesized in the testes.
[src:bile-acid/5α-androst-16-en-3α-ol] Pregnenolone is metabolized into androstadienol by the 16-ene-synthetase activity of CYP17A1.
[src:bile-acid/5α-androst-16-en-3α-ol] Androstenol may also be synthesized in the adrenal glands and the ovaries in humans.
[src:bile-acid/5α-androst-16-en-3α-ol] In addition, androstenol may be synthesized in the human nasal mucosa from androstenone, and likely also from androstadienol and androstadienone in this area.
[src:bile-acid/5α-androst-16-en-3α-ol] Considerable amounts of androstenol are present in human urine, and it is also present in the blood plasma and saliva of humans and pigs as well as in the axillary sweat of humans.
[src:bile-acid/5α-androst-16-en-3α-ol] Due to its ability to cross the blood–brain barrier, androstenol is likely present in the central nervous system as well.
[src:bile-acid/5α-androst-16-en-3α-ol] Androstenol, similarly to the related endogenous steroids 3α-androstanediol and androsterone, has been found to act as a potent positive allosteric modulator of the GABAA.
[src:bile-acid/5α-androst-16-en-3α-ol] It has been proposed that this action may mediate the pheromone effects of androstenol.
[src:bile-acid/5α-androst-16-en-3α-ol] Moreover, as androstadienol, androstadienone, and androstenone are all converted into androstenol, it could mediate their pheromone effects as well.
[src:bile-acid/5α-androst-16-en-3α-ol] In animals, androstenol has been found to produce anxiolytic-like, antidepressant-like, and anticonvulsant effects.
[src:bile-acid/5α-androst-16-en-3α-ol] Androstenol has also been found to modify the behavioral and social responses of humans.
[src:bile-acid/5α-androst-16-en-3α-ol] In addition, androstenol has been found to decrease luteinizing hormone (LH) pulse frequency during the follicular phase of the human menstrual cycle.
[src:bile-acid/5α-androst-16-en-3α-ol] In accordance, it has been proposed that androstenol may be involved in the menstrual synchrony of women.
[src:bile-acid/5α-androst-16-en-3α-ol] In contrast to androstenol (3α-androstenol), its 3β-epimer, 3β-androstenol, does not potentiate the GABAA receptor, even at high concentrations.
[src:bile-acid/5α-androst-16-en-3α-ol] This is in accordance with other 3β-hydroxy steroids, including isopregnanolone, epipregnanolone, 3β-dihydroprogesterone, and 3β-androstanediol, which similarly do not act as such, in contrast to their 3α-hydroxy variants.
[src:bile-acid/5α-androst-16-en-3α-ol] Androstenol is an antagonist of the constitutive androstane receptor (CAR).
[src:bile-acid/5α-androst-16-en-3α-ol] Androstenol has minimal or no androgenic activity.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Bile acids comprise about 80% of the organic compounds in bile (others are phospholipids and cholesterol).
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] An increased secretion of bile acids produces an increase in bile flow.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Bile acids facilitate digestion of dietary fats and oils.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] They serve as micelle-forming surfactants, which encapsulate nutrients, facilitating their absorption.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] These micelles are suspended in the chyme before further processing.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Bile acids also have hormonal actions throughout the body, particularly through the farnesoid X receptor and GPBAR1 (also known as TGR5).
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Bile acid synthesis occurs in liver cells, which synthesize *primary bile acids* (cholic acid and chenodeoxycholic acid in humans) via cytochrome P450-mediated oxidation of cholesterol in a multi-step process.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Approximately 600 mg of bile salts are synthesized daily to replace bile acids lost in the feces, although, as described below, much larger amounts are secreted, reabsorbed in the gut and recycled.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] The rate-limiting step in synthesis is the addition of a hydroxyl group of the 7th position of the steroid nucleus by the enzyme cholesterol 7 alpha-hydroxylase.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] This enzyme is down-regulated by cholic acid, up-regulated by cholesterol and is inhibited by the actions of the ileal hormone FGF15/19.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Prior to secreting any of the bile acids (primary or secondary, see below), liver cells conjugate them with either glycine or taurine, to form a total of 8 possible **conjugated primary bile acids**.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] These conjugated bile acids are often referred to as **bile salts**.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] The pKa of the unconjugated bile acids are between 5 and 6.5, and the pH of the duodenum ranges between 3 and 5, so when unconjugated bile acids are in the duodenum, they are almost always protonated (HA form), which makes them relatively insoluble in water.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Conjugating bile acids with amino acids lowers the pKa of the bile-acid/amino-acid conjugate to between 1 and 4.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Thus conjugated bile acids are almost always in their deprotonated (A-) form in the duodenum, which makes them much more water-soluble and much more able to fulfil their physiological function of emulsifying fats.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Once secreted into the lumen of the intestine, bile salts are modified by gut bacteria.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Their glycine and taurine groups are removed to give the *secondary bile acids*, deoxycholic acid and lithocholic acid.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Cholic acid is converted into deoxycholic acid and chenodeoxycholic acid into lithocholic acid.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] All four of these bile acids are recycled, in a process known as enterohepatic circulation.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] As molecules with hydrophobic and hydrophilic regions, conjugated bile salts sit at the lipid/water interface and, above the right concentration, form micelles.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] The added solubility of conjugated bile salts aids in their function by preventing passive re-absorption in the small intestine.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] As a result, the concentration of bile acids/salts in the small intestine is high enough to form micelles and solubilize lipids.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] "Critical micellar concentration" refers to both an intrinsic property of the bile acid itself and amount of bile acid necessary to function in the spontaneous and dynamic formation of micelles.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Bile acid-containing micelles aid lipases to digest lipids and bring them near the intestinal brush border membrane, which results in fat absorption.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Synthesis of bile acids is a major route of cholesterol metabolism in most species other than humans.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] The body produces about 800 mg of cholesterol per day and about half of that is used for bile acid synthesis producing 400–600 mg daily.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Human adults secrete between 12 and 18 g of bile acids into the intestine each day, mostly after meals.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] The bile acid pool size is between 4–6 g, which means that bile acids are recycled several times each day.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] About 95% of bile acids are reabsorbed by active transport in the ileum and recycled back to the liver for further secretion into the biliary system and gallbladder.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] This enterohepatic circulation of bile acids allows a low rate of synthesis, only about 0.3 g/day, but with large amounts being secreted into the intestine.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Bile acids have metabolic actions in the body resembling those of hormones, acting through two specific receptors, the farnesoid X receptor and G protein-coupled bile acid receptor TGR5.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Bile salts constitute a large family of molecules, composed of a steroid structure with four rings, a five- or eight-carbon side-chain terminating in a carboxylic acid, and several hydroxyl groups, the number and orientation of which is different among the specific bile salts.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] The four rings are labeled A, B, C, and D, from the farthest to the closest to the side chain with the carboxyl group.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] The D-ring is smaller by one carbon than the other three.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] The structure is commonly drawn with A at the left and D at the right.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] The hydroxyl groups can be in either of two configurations: either up (or out), termed beta (β; often drawn by convention as a solid line), or down, termed alpha (α; displayed as a dashed line).
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] All bile acids have a 3-hydroxyl group, derived from the parent molecule, cholesterol, in which the 3-hydroxyl is beta.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] The initial step in the classical pathway of hepatic synthesis of bile acids is the enzymatic addition of a 7α hydroxyl group by cholesterol 7α-hydroxylase (CYP7A1) forming 7α-hydroxycholesterol.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] This is then metabolised to 7α-hydroxy-4-cholesten-3-one.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] There are multiple steps in bile acid synthesis requiring 14 enzymes in all.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] These result in the junction between the first two steroid rings (A and B) being altered, making the molecule bent; in this process, the 3-hydroxyl is converted to the α orientation.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] The simplest 24-carbon bile acid has two hydroxyl groups at positions 3α and 7α.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] This is 3α,7α-dihydroxy-5β-cholan-24-oic acid, or, as more usually known, chenodeoxycholic acid.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] This bile acid was first isolated from the domestic goose, from which the "cheno" portion of the name was derived (Greek: χήν = goose).
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] The 5β in the name denotes the orientation of the junction between rings A and B of the steroid nucleus (in this case, they are bent).
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] The term "cholan" denotes a particular steroid structure of 24 carbons, and the "24-oic acid" indicates that the carboxylic acid is found at position 24, at the end of the side-chain.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Chenodeoxycholic acid is made by many species, and is the prototypic functional bile acid.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] An alternative (acidic) pathway of bile acid synthesis is initiated by mitochondrial sterol 27-hydroxylase (CYP27A1), expressed in liver, and also in macrophages and other tissues.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] CYP27A1 contributes significantly to total bile acid synthesis by catalyzing sterol side chain oxidation, after which cleavage of a three-carbon unit in the peroxisomes leads to formation of a C24 bile acid.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Minor pathways initiated by 25-hydroxylase in the liver and 24-hydroxylase in the brain also may contribute to bile acid synthesis.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] 7α-hydroxylase (CYP7B1) generates oxysterols, which may be further converted in the liver to CDCA.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Cholic acid, 3α,7α,12α-trihydroxy-5β-cholan-24-oic acid, the most abundant bile acid in humans and many other species, was discovered before chenodeoxycholic acid.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] It is a tri-hydroxy-bile acid with 3 hydroxyl groups (3α, 7α and 12α).
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] In its synthesis in the liver, 12α hydroxylation is performed by the additional action of CYP8B1.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] As this had already been described, the discovery of chenodeoxycholic acid (with 2 hydroxyl groups) made this new bile acid a "deoxycholic acid" in that it had one fewer hydroxyl group than cholic acid.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Deoxycholic acid is formed from cholic acid by 7-dehydroxylation, resulting in 2 hydroxyl groups (3α and 12α).
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] This process with chenodeoxycholic acid results in a bile acid with only a 3α hydroxyl group, termed lithocholic acid (litho = stone) having been identified first in a gallstone from a calf.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] It is poorly water-soluble and rather toxic to cells.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Different vertebrate families have evolved to use modifications of most positions on the steroid nucleus and side-chain of the bile acid structure.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] To avoid the problems associated with the production of lithocholic acid, most species add a third hydroxyl group to chenodeoxycholic acid.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] The subsequent removal of the 7α hydroxyl group by intestinal bacteria will then result in a less toxic but still-functional dihydroxy bile acid.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Over the course of vertebrate evolution, a number of positions have been chosen for placement of the third hydroxyl group.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Initially, the 16α position was favored, in particular in birds.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Later, this position was superseded in a large number of species selecting the 12α position.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Primates (including humans) utilize 12α for their third hydroxyl group position, producing cholic acid.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] In mice and other rodents, 6β hydroxylation forms muricholic acids (α or β depending on the 7 hydroxyl position).
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Pigs have 6α hydroxylation in hyocholic acid (3α,6α,7α-trihydroxy-5β-cholanoic acid), and other species have a hydroxyl group on position 23 of the side-chain.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Many other bile acids have been described, often in small amounts, resulting from bacterial enzymatic or other modifications.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] The "iso-" epimers have the 3-hydroxyl group in the β position.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] The "allo-" epimers have the 5α configuration, which changes the relative position of the A and B rings.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Ursodeoxycholic acid was first isolated from bear bile, which has been used medicinally for centuries.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Its structure resembles chenodeoxycholic acid but with the 7-hydroxyl group in the β position.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Obeticholic acid, 6α-ethyl-chenodeoxycholic acid, is a semi-synthetic bile acid with greater activity as an FXR agonist, which has been developed as a pharmaceutical agent in certain liver diseases.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Bile acids also act as steroid hormones, secreted from the liver, absorbed from the intestine and having various direct metabolic actions in the body through the nuclear receptor Farnesoid X receptor (FXR), also known by its gene name *NR1H4*.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Another bile acid receptor is the cell membrane receptor known as G protein-coupled bile acid receptor 1 or TGR5.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Many of their functions as signaling molecules in the liver and the intestines are by activating FXR, whereas TGR5 may be involved in metabolic, endocrine and neurological functions.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] As surfactants or detergents, bile acids are potentially toxic to cells, and so their concentrations are tightly regulated.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Activation of FXR in the liver inhibits synthesis of bile acids, and is one mechanism of feedback control when bile acid levels are too high.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Secondly, FXR activation by bile acids during absorption in the intestine increases transcription and synthesis of FGF19, which then inhibits bile acid synthesis in the liver.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Emerging evidence associates FXR activation with alterations in triglyceride metabolism, glucose metabolism, and liver growth.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Bile acids bind to some other proteins in addition to their hormone receptors (FXR and TGR5) and their transporters.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Among these protein targets, the membrane enzyme N-acyl phosphatidylethanolamine-specific phospholipase D (NAPE-PLD) of the endocannabinoid system.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Bile acids are essential confactors for the biogenesis of lipid signaling amides (e.g., Anandamide, Palmitoylethanolamide, Oleoylethanolamide) mediated by NAPE-PLD.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] These lipid molecules (e.g. the endogenous cannabinoid anandamide) have important roles in several physiological pathways including stress and pain responses, appetite, and lifespan.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] NAPE-PLD thus facilitates crosstalk between bile acids signals and lipid amide signals.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] The interaction between enzyme and bile acids stabilizes the protein dimer, promoting its association to membrane phospholipids and the key role of NAPE-PLD in antihypertensive therapy and neurovascular protection.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] As bile acids are made from endogenous cholesterol, disruption of the enterohepatic circulation of bile acids will lower cholesterol.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Bile acid sequestrants bind bile acids in the gut, preventing reabsorption.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] In so doing, more endogenous cholesterol is shunted into the production of bile acids, thereby lowering cholesterol levels.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] The sequestered bile acids are then excreted in the feces.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Tests for bile acids are useful in both human and veterinary medicine, as they aid in the diagnosis of a number of conditions, including types of cholestasis such as intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy, portosystemic shunt, and hepatic microvascular dysplasia in dogs.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Structural or functional abnormalities of the biliary system result in an increase in bilirubin (jaundice) and in bile acids in the blood.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Bile acids are related to the itching (pruritus) which is common in cholestatic conditions such as primary biliary cirrhosis (PBC), primary sclerosing cholangitis or intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Treatment with ursodeoxycholic acid has been used for many years in these cholestatic disorders.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] The relationship of bile acids to cholesterol saturation in bile and cholesterol precipitation to produce gallstones has been studied extensively.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Gallstones may result from increased saturation of cholesterol or bilirubin, or from bile stasis.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Lower concentrations of bile acids or phospholipids in bile reduce cholesterol solubility and lead to microcrystal formation.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Oral therapy with chenodeoxycholic acid and/or ursodeoxycholic acid has been used to dissolve cholesterol gallstones.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Stones may recur when treatment is stopped.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Bile acid therapy may be of value to prevent stones in certain circumstances such as following bariatric surgery.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Excess concentrations of bile acids in the colon are a cause of chronic diarrhea.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] It is commonly found when the ileum is abnormal or has been surgically removed, as in Crohn's disease, or cause a condition that resembles diarrhea-predominant irritable bowel syndrome (IBS-D).
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] This condition of bile acid diarrhea/bile acid malabsorption can be diagnosed by the SeHCAT test and treated with bile acid sequestrants.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Bile acids may have some importance in the development of colorectal cancer.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Deoxycholic acid is increased in the colonic contents of humans in response to a high fat diet.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] In populations with a high incidence of colorectal cancer, fecal concentrations of bile acids are higher, particularly deoxycholic acid.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] The effects of ursodeoxycholic acid in modifying the risk of colorectal cancer is under study, particularly in primary sclerosing cholangitis and inflammatory bowel disease, with varying results partly related to dosage.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] A 2025 meta-analysis on the relationship of fecal bile acid concentrations to the development and progression of colorectal cancer found that higher fecal concentrations of cholic acid and chenodeoxycholic acid are associated with a higher risk and higher incidence of colorectal cancer.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Accumulating evidence also indicates that the gut microbiota can influence the distribution of bile acids in the colon and thus are a significant factor in colorectal cancer development.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Bile acids have not only been implicated as carcinogens in the colon but also at other sites in the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Bile acids may be used in subcutaneous injections to remove unwanted fat (see Mesotherapy).
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Deoxycholic acid as an injectable has received FDA approval to dissolve submental fat.
[src:bile-acid/bile-acid] Phase III trials showed significant responses although many subjects had mild adverse reactions of bruising, swelling, pain, numbness, erythema, and firmness around the treated area.
